        <tr> 
          <td colspan="3" align="RIGHT" valign="top"> 
            <p align=LEFT><b><font color="#0c2d83" size="+1" face="Times New Roman, Times, serif">case 
              summaries</font></b> 
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80" valign="top"><a name="1"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Civil 
            Rights </font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td colspan="3" valign="top"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font size="2"><b><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">This 
              summary also appears under Employment &amp; Labor Law</font></b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Same-sex sexual harassment; Judgment as a matter of law in favor 
              of employer on basis alleged harasser was not employee’s supervisor 
              and the employee did not report the behavior to the employer; Burden 
              of proving that conduct at issue constituted discrimination because 
              of sex as required under Title VII; Jury instructions; <i>Oncale 
              v. Sundowner Offshore Servs., Inc.</i>; Damages<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>U.S. Court of Appeals Sixth Circuit<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Equal Employment Opportunity Comm’n v. Harbert-Yeargin, 
              Inc.<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12367<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Gilman; Concurring in part, Dissenting in part – Guy and Norris</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Judgment as 
              a matter of law was properly granted to defendant-employer regarding 
              the EEOC’s claim on behalf of one of defendant’s employees, Woods, 
              on the grounds that the alleged harasser, Davis, was not Woods’s 
              supervisor and that Woods never voiced a contemporaneous complaint 
              to defendant regarding Davis’s conduct. The EEOC failed to show 
              that defendant knew or should have known about Davis’s groping of 
              Woods. It was undisputed that Woods never reported the behavior 
              to defendant’s administration, and although the EEOC argued that 
              constructive notice could be found because other employees witnessed 
              the challenged conduct, there was no proof that these other employees 
              were supervisors. The court reversed the jury verdict in favor of 
              another employee, Carlton, because plaintiff did not sustain the 
              burden of proving that the conduct at issue actually constituted 
              discrimination because of sex. </font></p>
            <p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/us_appeals/2001/092101/12367.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font><br>
<hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80" valign="top"><a name="2"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Constitutional 
            Law </font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="top"> 
          <td colspan="3"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><b><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">This summary 
              also appears under Municipal</font></b></p>
            <p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Challenge to denial of application for rezoning; Alleged Fifth 
              Amendment violation; Alleged due process violation of the Fourteenth 
              Amendment; Alleged violations of §§ 1983 and 1988; The <i>Rooker/Feldman</i> 
              abstention doctrine; The <i>Pullman</i> abstention doctrine; The 
              <i>England</i> doctrine; Whether the district court erred in dismissing 
              the due process argument against the state trial court</font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><br>
              Court: </b>U.S. Court of Appeals Sixth Circuit<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Anderson v. Charter Twp. of Ypsilanti<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12369<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Gilman, Clay, and Wallace</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">After analyzing 
              Michigan and federal regulatory-takings law, as well as the specific 
              rulings of the Michigan state trial and appellate courts, the court 
              concluded that the district court's dismissal on the basis of the 
              <i>Rooker/Feldman</i> abstention doctrine was correct in hindsight, 
              even if premature, because the Michigan Court of Appeals considered 
              plaintiff's claim of a noncategorical deprivation. The issue was 
              whether the district court's conclusions regarding plaintiff's federal 
              takings claim placed it in the position of evaluating the merits 
              of the state trial court's decision. At the time of the district 
              court's order, no state court had ruled on plaintiff's noncategorical 
              takings claim. Had the Michigan Court of Appeals not ruled on this 
              issue, a serious question would have been presented concerning the 
              district court's dismissal of the action. Affirmed. </font></p>
            <p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/us_appeals/2001/092101/12369.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font><br>
<hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80" valign="top"><a name="3"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Contracts</font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="top"> 
          <td colspan="3"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font size="2"><b><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">This 
              summary also appears under Litigation</font></b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Arbitration; Whether arbitrator exceeded his authority in determining 
              plaintiff to be the "prevailing party" and awarding attorney fees 
              and costs; Whether arbitrator ignored evidence; Refusal to consider 
              material evidence; Evidence offered after arbitration hearing had 
              closed<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>Michigan Court of Appeals (Unpublished)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Harmon v. Millman-Derr Ctrs. for Eye Care, P.C.<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12382<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Per Curiam - Kelly, Hood, and Zahra</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The arbitrator 
              did not exceed his authority when he determined that plaintiff was 
              the "prevailing party" and awarded attorney fees and costs. The 
              power to award attorney fees and costs was proper because it was 
              within the arbitrator's authority based on the arbitration agreement. 
              The contract interpretation of the term "prevailing party" presented 
              a question for the arbitrator, which the court was precluded from 
              deciding. The authority to award the attorney fees and costs did 
              not arise from MCR 2.625, but rather from the arbitration agreement 
              in the contract. There also was no indication that the arbitrator 
              ignored the evidence and relied solely on his experience. The arbitrator 
              examined the evidence, found that the plaintiff's testimony was 
              credible, then noted that the testimony was consistent with the 
              arbitrator's experience. Affirmed.</font></p>
            <p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/appeals/2001/092101/12382.pdf">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font><br>
<hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80" valign="top"><a name="4"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Criminal 
            Law </font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td colspan="3" valign="top"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="2"><b><font size="3">Issues: 
              </font></b><font size="3">Denial of motion for a mistrial; Use of 
              photograph in assisting witness to identify victim; Constitutional 
              challenges to Michigan’s automatic waiver process; <i>People v. 
              Conat<br>
              </i></font></font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>Michigan Court of Appeals (Unpublished)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>People v. Hynes<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12383<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Per Curiam – O’Connell, White, and Smolenski</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The prosecutor’s 
              use of a photograph of the victim to assist the victim’s mother 
              in identifying her daughter while testifying was proper. The prosecutor 
              showed the witness a photograph of the victim taken during her high 
              school senior year, but did not introduce the photograph into evidence 
              or publish it to the jury. The witness began to cry, and several 
              spectators also reacted emotionally. The trial court immediately 
              called a recess, and when proceedings resumed, the prosecutor asked 
              no further questions concerning the photograph. The court noted 
              that the victim’s mother was the only witness to testify from personal 
              knowledge regarding the victim’s identity. Further, the display 
              of emotion was not gratuitous and was immediately halted by the 
              trial court. The court held that no prejudice occurred. Defendant’s 
              conviction of first-degree murder was affirmed.</font></p>
            <p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/appeals/2001/092101/12383.pdf">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font><br>
<hr>
            <font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
            to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> 
            <p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Trial court’s refusal to conduct an <i>in camera</i> review 
              of the complainants’ privileged records for exculpatory evidence; 
              Limitation on cross-examination of one complainant in CSC case regarding 
              multiple drug delivery offenses<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>Michigan Court of Appeals (Unpublished)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>People v. Stuckmann<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12392<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Per Curiam – Cavanagh, Markey, and Cooper</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The trial court 
              did not abuse its discretion in denying defendant’s discovery motion 
              without prejudice in this CSC case and in failing to conduct an 
              <i>in camera</i> review of the complainants’ privileged records 
              to determine whether exculpatory evidence was present. Defendant’s 
              discovery request was not based on any demonstrable fact in support 
              of the defense theory, but was instead intended as a mere fishing 
              expedition. The trial court also did not abuse its discretion in 
              limiting cross-examination of one of the complainant’s regarding 
              multiple drug delivery offenses that complainant admitted to committing, 
              but for which he was not prosecuted. Such cross-examination was 
              not relevant or probative. Defense counsel was allowed extensive 
              cross-examination regarding the plea agreement therefore, the jury 
              was made aware of that complainant’s possible motive to fabricate. 
              Defendant’s convictions were affirmed. </font></p>
            <p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/appeals/2001/092101/12392.pdf">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font><br>
<hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80" valign="top"><a name="5"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Employment 
