            <p><b><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">This summary 
              also appears under Civil Rights</font></b></p>
            <p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Same-sex sexual harassment; Judgment as a matter of law in favor 
              of employer on basis alleged harasser was not employee’s supervisor 
              and the employee did not report the behavior to the employer; Burden 
              of proving that conduct at issue constituted discrimination because 
              of sex as required under Title VII; Jury instructions; <i>Oncale 
              v. Sundowner Offshore Servs., Inc.</i>; Damages<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>U.S. Court of Appeals Sixth Circuit<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Equal Employment Opportunity Comm’n v. Harbert-Yeargin, 
              Inc.<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12367<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Gilman; Concurring in part, Dissenting in part – Guy and Norris</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Judgment as 
              a matter of law was properly granted to defendant-employer regarding 
              the EEOC’s claim on behalf of one of defendant’s employees, Woods, 
              on the grounds that the alleged harasser, Davis, was not Woods’s 
              supervisor and that Woods never voiced a contemporaneous complaint 
              to defendant regarding Davis’s conduct. The EEOC failed to show 
              that defendant knew or should have known about Davis’s groping of 
              Woods. It was undisputed that Woods never reported the behavior 
              to defendant’s administration, and although the EEOC argued that 
              constructive notice could be found because other employees witnessed 
              the challenged conduct, there was no proof that these other employees 
              were supervisors. The court reversed the jury verdict in favor of 
              another employee, Carlton, because plaintiff did not sustain the 
              burden of proving that the conduct at issue actually constituted 
              discrimination because of sex. </font></p>
            <p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/us_appeals/2001/092101/12367.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font><br>
