        <tr> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80" valign="top"><a name="6"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Litigation</font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="top"> 
          <td colspan="3"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="2"><b><font size="3">Issues: 
              </font></b><font size="3">Dismissal with prejudice as a sanction 
              for obstruction of discovery<br>
              </font></font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>Michigan Court of Appeals (Unpublished)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Al-Isawi v. McCann<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12386<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Per Curiam – Cavanagh, Markey, and Cooper</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The trial court 
              did not abuse its discretion in dismissing plaintiffs’ action with 
              prejudice due to their obstruction of discovery. Plaintiffs’ delays 
              and denials of discovery extended throughout the case. They failed 
              to supply full and complete answers to interrogatories as ordered, 
              and their supplemental answers failed to cure most of the defects. 
              Plaintiffs would not disclose the nature of their injuries, the 
              names of witnesses, or what serious impairment of body function 
              they were claiming. They also failed to show up for court-ordered 
              medical examinations, and the trial court’s less drastic sanction 
              of assessing $1,000 in costs proved unsuccessful. While plaintiffs 
              now argued that they could not afford to pay those court-ordered 
              costs, they did not claim indigency at the time of the order. Affirmed.</font></p>
            <p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/appeals/2001/092101/12386.pdf">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font><br>
<hr>
            <font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
            to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> 
            <p><b><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">This summary 
              also appears under Contracts</font></b></p>
            <p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Arbitration; Whether arbitrator exceeded his authority in determining 
              plaintiff to be the "prevailing party" and awarding attorney fees 
              and costs; Whether arbitrator ignored evidence; Refusal to consider 
              material evidence; Evidence offered after arbitration hearing had 
              closed<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>Michigan Court of Appeals (Unpublished)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Harmon v. Millman-Derr Ctrs. for Eye Care, P.C.<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12382<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Per Curiam - Kelly, Hood, and Zahra</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The arbitrator 
              did not exceed his authority when he determined that plaintiff was 
              the "prevailing party" and awarded attorney fees and costs. The 
              power to award attorney fees and costs was proper because it was 
              within the arbitrator's authority based on the arbitration agreement. 
              The contract interpretation of the term "prevailing party" presented 
              a question for the arbitrator, which the court was precluded from 
              deciding. The authority to award the attorney fees and costs did 
              not arise from MCR 2.625, but rather from the arbitration agreement 
              in the contract. There also was no indication that the arbitrator 
              ignored the evidence and relied solely on his experience. The arbitrator 
              examined the evidence, found that the plaintiff's testimony was 
              credible, then noted that the testimony was consistent with the 
              arbitrator's experience. Affirmed.</font></p>
            <p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/appeals/2001/092101/12382.pdf">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font><br>
