        <tr valign="top"> 
          <td colspan="3"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><b><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">This summary 
              also appears under Constitutional Law</font></b></p>
            <p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Challenge to denial of application for rezoning; Alleged Fifth 
              Amendment violation; Alleged due process violation of the Fourteenth 
              Amendment; Alleged violations of §§ 1983 and 1988; The <i>Rooker/Feldman</i> 
              abstention doctrine; The <i>Pullman</i> abstention doctrine; The 
              <i>England</i> doctrine; Whether the district court erred in dismissing 
              the due process argument against the state trial court<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>U.S. Court of Appeals Sixth Circuit<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Anderson v. Charter Twp. of Ypsilanti<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12369<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Gilman, Clay, and Wallace</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">After analyzing 
              Michigan and federal regulatory-takings law, as well as the specific 
              rulings of the Michigan state trial and appellate courts, the court 
              concluded that the district court's dismissal on the basis of the 
              <i>Rooker/Feldman</i> abstention doctrine was correct in hindsight, 
              even if premature, because the Michigan Court of Appeals considered 
              plaintiff's claim of a noncategorical deprivation. The issue was 
              whether the district court's conclusions regarding plaintiff's federal 
              takings claim placed it in the position of evaluating the merits 
              of the state trial court's decision. At the time of the district 
              court's order, no state court had ruled on plaintiff's noncategorical 
              takings claim. Had the Michigan Court of Appeals not ruled on this 
              issue, a serious question would have been presented concerning the 
              district court's dismissal of the action. Affirmed. </font></p>
            <p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/us_appeals/2001/092101/12369.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font><br>
