        <tr> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80" valign="top"><a name="8"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Real 
            Property </font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td colspan="3" valign="top"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><b><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">This summary 
              also appears under Tax</font></b></p>
            <p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Action to quiet title;<b> </b>Notice of reconveyance after obtaining 
              tax deed (MCL 211.73a)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>Michigan Court of Appeals (Unpublished)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Burkhardt v. Bailey<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12388<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Per Curiam - Cavanagh, Markey, and Cooper</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The trial court 
              correctly granted summary disposition in favor of defendant-Bond 
              Corporation, the mortgage holder, and dismissed the case, but erred 
              in declaring plaintiff's tax deed void because there was still time 
              under the statute to give the required notice. If plaintiff fails 
              to serve the required statutory notice on Bond within the specified 
              five-year period, he will be barred from claiming title to the property 
              under the tax deed. The trial court erred in granting summary disposition 
              in favor of defendant-Bailey, the property owner, who failed to 
              pay property taxes, because he took no steps to redeem the property 
              within six months of receiving the notice of redemption. Bailey 
              lost the opportunity to redeem the property when he failed to act 
              in a timely manner and was not entitled to rely on Bond's argument 
              that it did not receive proper notice. Affirmed in part and reversed 
              in part.</font></p>
            <p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"> <b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/appeals/2001/092101/12388.pdf">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font><br>
                        <hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80" valign="top"><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><a name="9"></a><b>Tax</b></font></td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td colspan="3" valign="top"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><b><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">This summary 
              also appears under Real Property</font></b></p>
            <p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Action to quiet title;<b> </b>Notice of reconveyance after obtaining 
              tax deed (MCL 211.73a)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>Michigan Court of Appeals (Unpublished)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Burkhardt v. Bailey<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12388<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Per Curiam - Cavanagh, Markey, and Cooper</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The trial court 
              correctly granted summary disposition in favor of defendant-Bond 
              Corporation, the mortgage holder, and dismissed the case, but erred 
              in declaring plaintiff's tax deed void because there was still time 
              under the statute to give the required notice. If plaintiff fails 
              to serve the required statutory notice on Bond within the specified 
              five-year period, he will be barred from claiming title to the property 
              under the tax deed. The trial court erred in granting summary disposition 
              in favor of defendant-Bailey, the property owner, who failed to 
              pay property taxes, because he took no steps to redeem the property 
              within six months of receiving the notice of redemption. Bailey 
              lost the opportunity to redeem the property when he failed to act 
              in a timely manner and was not entitled to rely on Bond's argument 
              that it did not receive proper notice. Affirmed in part and reversed 
              in part.</font></p>
            <p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"> <b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/appeals/2001/092101/12388.pdf">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font><br>
<hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
